title="Alex Nelson">Alex Nelson</fr:link></fr:author></fr:authors></fr:frontmatter><fr:mainmatter><fr:p>We need to prove this is actually a group and it is commutative.</fr:p>
<fr:p><fr:strong>Claim 1: it is a group.</fr:strong> Suffices to show the binary operator of <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[G]]></fr:tex> is closed on this set and <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[e\in  G]]></fr:tex> and it contains all its inverses. The binary operator of <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[G]]></fr:tex> is clearly closed on this set by the <fr:link
type="local"
href="gr-000L.xml"
addr="gr-000L"
title="Product law">Product law</fr:link> and <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[g^{0}=e]]></fr:tex> so the identity element belongs to it. Further, if <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[g^{n}\in \langle  g\rangle ]]></fr:tex>, then its inverse <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[g^{-n}\in \langle  g\rangle ]]></fr:tex> clearly belongs to it. Hence this is really a group.</fr:p>
<fr:p><fr:strong>Claim 2: it is commutative.</fr:strong> We see for any arbitrary <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[g^{m}g^{n}=g^{m+n}=g^{n+m}=g^{n}g^{m}]]></fr:tex> by the <fr:link
type="local"
href="gr-000L.xml"
addr="gr-000L"
title="Product law">Product law</fr:link> and the commutativity of addition for integers.</fr:p><html:span
